text:
i feel this way all the time. i've survived two sexual assaults and two counts of domestic violence. i've blamed myself for 20 years for the first rape that happened at age 12. and i blame myself for falling for the love bombing of an abuser (twice). i constantly replay traumas over in my head trying to figure them out. asking "why didn't i fight harder", "why didn't i leave earlier", "maybe if i'd said no more forcefully instead of freezing", "what's wrong with me?". and for 20 years, i've kept secrets from people who have been friends, boyfriends etc. because i believed (and still do) that if anyone ever really knew me, or knew my history, the things i've "done", how "bad" i am...no one could ever want or love me. i'm broken and damaged, and difficult. 
so to every person who has reached, to the ones who make it a point to let me know i'm cared about...thank you...even if i withdraw, isolate myself, push you away before you can leave me...thank you anyway. i owe you my life. 
#ptsd #bpd #borderlinepersonalitydisorder #borderline #actuallyborderline #mentalhealth #mentalillness #survivor #trauma #endthestigma #breakthestigma #mentalhealthawareness #violenceagainstwomen #posttraumaticstressdisorder #fighter #depression #depressed #metoo

everyday on the roads cars beep at me, guys yell something, even guys passing by say "hello" in a very sleazy way. i just roll my eyes too jaded to even get angry anymore. what do you expect is going to happen? incredible. today was walking home after dark, a van stopped and this guy yelled get on! come on! um i don't think so buddy. #metoo
.
i like to walk around. it's free, it's the only exercise i get, it's therapeutic, i discover things you don't notice driving. i like ports where i'm not harassed and people leave me alone.
.
top 3 favourite are
1) monte carlo,
2) messina,
3) fanning island.
.
top 3 worst are
1) kusadasi (omg i actually hate michael kors after streets full of vendors grabbing you to see their mk knockoffs),
2) puntaneras (beautiful beach but pervert experience totally spoilt it),
3) laem chabang ("no i dont want tuk tuk, who is tuk tuk?" funniest thing a friend said)
.
what are your top 3s?
.

remember that you too can make an impact on the role and lives of women in your own circles, our community or internationally. women have made great strides in helping one another, becoming mentors, and making an outstanding impact in communities across our province and this great country.

text:
i look at the many things you have given me.
the books on my shelves. 
the floorboards under my feet.
the right to call them my own. 
to be recognized for such ownership. 
the ballot, mailed to me and not to my husband. 
the methods available that give me the right to choose
when and how i become a vessel for another life.
i recognize the privilege that time has allowed me.
i do not take for granted the ones who fought and died,
in the hope they would ensure these freedoms.
if you think i speak to you,
then you know not to whom i speak. 
it is not you i have to thank. 
you did not endow me with these freedoms.
these privileges were not concessions,
or brought about by compromise. 
they were hard fought and hard won.
forced off your tongues and into your quills. 
i have you to thank, only for the fuel that fed this fire. 
thank you for teaching me,
what i have a right to be angry for,
and who deserves the brunt of it. 
i want more. 
i want safety and surety.
that does not depend on your ability,
to control your impulses. 
i want your word,
that you will let me take these freedoms,
hard won and rightfully mine,
and leave me be. 
i already know how you will answer,
so i will keep asking.
until you tell me what i want to hear. ‚Äúthe rights of women‚Äù photo by josh johnson on @unsplash

#womensrights #womenempowerment #womeninpower #poetry #metoo

i sat down. several weeks ago. to stamp out my reasons. starting from when i was a small child.  i worked non-stop for four hours. half way through my 16th year, i had to start climbing the sides of the pan for space.

it was 5 years before anita hill.

i'm now near 50 years old. i could easily fill another vessel. or two. and here we are. again. still. watching an entire nation get gaslit. to protect a frat house to whitehouse pipeline. built. right through women's lives and over our bodies. 
this cannot continue.

we are not going back.

we only go forward.

the only way out is through. 
#ibelievesurvivors

text: i thank god every day that i get to exist in a marriage where the respect is fully mutual.  i get to be strong and powerful and independent and so does he.  i get to be 100% authentically myself and so does he.  my success is celebrated and so is his.  i get to voice my opinions and have them listened to and so does he.  i have my wounds salved and my sorrow comforted and so does he.  i get to talk about my #metoo stories and feel heard and believed and validated.  the strongest men and women lift each other up every day and i am so grateful this is my life and he is my husband because up until we came into each other's life, it never was this way.  #metoo #marriage #believewomen #menneedlovetoo #nomoreoldboysclub

text:
okay let‚Äôs talk. 
history and current news show that rapists, assailants, and perpetrators are allowed to walk free, and sometimes even thrive in life, with no repercussions. even if ppl believe us, society has proved that they don‚Äôt care enough to protect or serve justice to you. our own system will look the other way in order to benefit their own agenda. 
people see the #metoo hashtags, the outrage, and advocacy, but not the ptsd, anxiety, and years of reliving the trauma that interfere with our whole lives. 
so this is an active reminder during this trying time... it‚Äôs okay to avoid the news and not speak about topics that are traumatic to you.
i literally can‚Äôt stand what‚Äôs been happening recently & i can‚Äôt get myself to watch the news bc it triggers my ptsd. 
simple reminders: it‚Äôs okay and important to seek help. having someone validate and understand your experience is an essential part of healing. it‚Äôs also okay to cut out those around you who are detrimental to your recovery ‚ÄºÔ∏è
it is not your fault and you can regain control of your life. others can tell you otherwise, and it‚Äôs important to set boundaries on how much opinions you want to consumeüò∂
ppl roll their eyes when we talk abt ‚Äútriggers‚Äù, ‚Äúsafe-spaces‚Äù, and ‚Äúself-care‚Äù, but we say fuck you bc they don‚Äôt know the shit we‚Äôve been thru üíÖüèº
i believe you. i will listen to you. 
my dms are always open to anyone who needs protection or to just talk!!!

text: i think every female i know can relate to #metoo. not because every woman has been raped. but i would venture to guess that 90% of women have been sexually assaulted to some degree. whether they have had their breast‚Äôs grazed while on the subway or had their ass blatantly slapped, or have been on the verge of being raped before fate stepped in. about two years ago i posted something about being sexually assaulted (verbally) by a male on the street and a female responded by saying ‚Äòyou should be happy, it‚Äôs a compliment‚Äô. i almost second guessed myself. just like i have on all of the other times i‚Äôve been targeted and assaulted by men. blaming myself, wondering if what i‚Äôm wearing causes the behavior, wondering if i walk differently or wear no makeup or only wear sweatpants it will make a difference. it doesn‚Äôt. it maybe never will. it doesn‚Äôt even matter if i‚Äôm holding hands with my boyfriend down the street. it still happens. just as it does to millions of other women. maybe sometimes our stories don‚Äôt make sense to you. details may be missing or time frames might not make sense. but they are our stories. and our feelings. and you can‚Äôt fucking argue with how i feel. and you certainly cannot ever tell me how to feel about being a woman. i love being a woman; being the only way that humanity enters into existence of this tired world we live in. but i also hate it. i hate that i might have a daughter one day and know that she may also be a statistic.  maybe you don‚Äôt want to believe the truth... that women are second class citizens in our society.... that we all have a #metoo story. but we do. i hope that we can come together and make this shift and change. the only thing i can continue to do until then is believe and support. the only thing we can do is create a sisterhood. peace to all.

text: six months ago i sat outside a hotel on 54th street covered in my own puke and tears, blaming myself for something i thought i could have prevented. for six months i have been adjusting to a new life of anxiety and depression. i have felt lower lows than i ever thought i would. i have thought about what happened to me that night every single day for the past six months. six months ago, i was raped. i was not drunk or drugged. it didn‚Äôt happen the way it is portrayed in movies and tv shows. i trusted a seemingly nice boy and willingly joined him in his hotel room for what i thought would be ‚Äúa movie and take out‚Äù. this was admittedly not the best decision i have made, but by no means was going into his hotel room consent for him to do what he did to me. i repeatedly told him no and asked him to stop. i cried but instead of stopping he turned me on my stomach so that i could not move, speak, and i quickly became short of breath and so afraid that i completely blacked out. there are things that i can‚Äôt remember and although i wish i didn‚Äôt remember any of it, it‚Äôs not being able to recall what happened to me in those moments that i fear the most. the bruises he left have disappeared but the emotional scaring have made a permanent mark on my mental health. i forced myself to relive this moment time and time again by telling many different people of authority. coming to the decision to make a report in the first place was such a battle for me because that meant that it actually did happen and that it was real, going through the process of telling it over and over in graphic detail was emotionally taxing, but the most heart breaking and devastating part of it all was when i was told that there really wasn‚Äôt any proof and it sounded like it was ‚Äúa super unfortunate misunderstanding‚Äù. i was raped. it was intentional. i had my innocence stripped away from me in a horrific way. being brave enough to stand up for yourself and tell your story is hard but when people don‚Äôt believe you, it‚Äôs heartbreaking. 1 in 5 people are raped. it happens all the time with seemingly no consequences. abusers walk away unharmed and the victims have to find a way to survive and cope with it

text: this is precisely why survivors like myself are mad as hell. our assaults aren‚Äôt incorrectly recollected memories, null nightmares, or void vilifications. our stories are personifications of deeply embedded trauma‚Äîtrauma that is all too often gaslit first by our abusers who hide in plain sight, and ultimately by supremely broadcasted abusers of judicial/legislative/executive power, into silence. but it‚Äôs never silent for us, it can‚Äôt be conveniently swept aside, we can‚Äôt resume business as usual. their blissfully ignorant silence is our deafening knowledge that justice will never be served, introducing a whole new searing internal trauma that we alone are burdened to pigeonhole. and in between our perps and our highest courts in the land are all of you fucking idiots who genuinely believe that vocal assault victims are the result of a get rich quick pyramid scheme so you‚Äôd sooner believe a man you‚Äôve never met than a woman you‚Äôve never met. and that‚Äôs a word. thank you @time for this powerful image. thank you #pamelameyer for haunting me with your talk for the last six years and inspiring me to flex my frustrations in premiere tonight. #metoo.

this is lashonda childs, 17, of dayton, ohio. she was murdered two days before her 18th birthday by her ex-boyfriend, who has a history of domestic violence against her. lashonda died early wednesday morning after she was shot tuesday. she called 911 before the shooting, giving the dispatcher 28-year-old trendell goodwin‚Äôs name and description.
.
‚Äúthis dude got a gun pointed to my boyfriend‚Äôs head,‚Äù lashonda told the 911 dispatcher. ‚Äúi‚Äôve got a restraining order on him. the police told me to call when i see him. i gave you the address. can‚Äôt you just send somebody out there? i‚Äôm scared. he‚Äôs got a gun. i can‚Äôt talk ‚Ä¶ i can‚Äôt talk. i‚Äôm in a bad situation.‚Äù her death was ruled a homicide due to a gunshot wound to the head.
.

.
on feb. 19, 2018, goodwin was arrested after lashonda told police he hit her in the face and bit her left shoulder during an argument about text messages involving another woman.
‚Äúchilds had a fresh bite mark on her left shoulder. the left side of her face was swollen where she claimed goodwin hit her. she also had abrasions on the right side of her neck and her nose was bleeding at one point,‚Äù a dayton police officer wrote. goodwin was arrested that day. he served 19 days of a 180-day sentence for misdemeanor assault. goodwin was ordered not to have contact with lashonda, received home detention and was ordered to receive counseling.
.

text:
@regran_ed from @afrogirlfitness -  this is both saddening and infuriating .
via: @sheisestella i personally witnessed the death of a black mother who delivered twins by c-section. she was groaning loudly (as you would when you're in pain) in the ward for over an hour while nurses and midwives carried on with their duties; turning a blind a eye to her.
i had also delivered my first son by c-section on the same day and was brought to the icu (intensive care unit) where i watched the incident unfold from across the room. 
after an hour or more of consistent groaning and slithering on her bed, alarms signalled and our room curtains were speedily drawn to close while she was taken away by emergency staff. a midwife later made known to us that she'd passed away.
this incident affected me massively. i carried a lot of fear and anxeity during my week stay at the hospital and in my subsequent pregnancies; all as a result of the incident. .
#blackmothers #blacklivesmatter #metoo #serenawilliams #afrogirlfitness - #regrann

text:
the day this picture was taken my entire life changed for ever.
i lost my best friend and had to become stronger without knowing the meaning of it. 
little i knew that i was going to become a victim of sexual assault at such a young age by family members, then by an ex.
little i knew about taking time to understand and heal (there was nothing wrong with me, you know?)
i lived in perpetual pain without knowing it. people judged me and still does (bc they don't know shit). i mean, i do it all the time to myself (but bc i blame myself or used to).
little i knew that i was going to lose people on the way of standing for myself (but that's ok, they all can fuck off #truecolors).
but little i knew that in all that pain and darkness, i was going to find myself, become a better person and help others. 
little i knew about the freedom and courage i was going to find within me (i had nothing to lose anymore).
now, i understand that people don't get what they can't deal with.
life is too short for dwelling into the past. let that shit go. let yourself soar into greatness, your greatness.

i am #metoo, and before you ask me again "why it took me so long" or "why i didn't do anything to stop it", i am telling you now, that maybe i didn't talk "earlier" because of people like you (look closer), everyone has their own process and my past does not define me. 
and to all the victims, you are not alone. i feel you, man. and i am sorry that happened to you, no one deserves it. let yourself be happy and live your best life.
hit me up when feeling down. i won't have the answers, but i can listen and be empathetic.
love your wounds. love yourself like no one ever will.
we are not victims, we are survivors, we are mother-fucking-badass warriors.

text:
the scottsboro boys were a group of 9 black teens, who were convicted in a democrat state, of rape, in 1931. they were falsely accused of rape by two white women, ruby bates & victoria price, who said the boys raped them on a train. 
in the first set of trials in april 1931, a jury quickly convicted the scottsboro boys and sentenced eight of them to death. the boys' lives were destroyed. the women later admitted their allegations were false. all of the scottsboro boys served prison time. convictions were overturned and the charges finally dropped in 1937 for 5 of the boys. it would take until 2013 for the state to issue posthumous pardons for the remaining three accused. 
when women lie, good men die.

oh, what happened to the women who lied? they faded into obscurity, changed their names, married and lived long lives. with no consequences. so, remember this story the next time you hear feminists screaming "we believe survivors." #himtoo #enough #confirmkavanaugh #kavanaughnow  #istandwithbrett #dueprocessmatters #dueprocess #democrats #republicans #metoo #womensmarch #maga #walkaway

text: isn't everyone pissed off about our geriatric, pathetic, white male leaders?  potus and sex offender, defending a fellow sex offender!  frat boy mentality running our country...disgraceful!  what?!?! youre not infuriated? who is going to listen to and believe your daughters when this happens to them?  are they going to be able to count on us to defend them and have their back or will you dismiss them as well.  i can't believe some of the rhetoric i hear from people i know...making jokes about sexual abuse and assault. its not funny.  its happened to more women than you could ever imagine...your mothers, your sisters, your daughters.  but you've probably never heard about it because statistically the abused never say a word...why?  because we don't listen to them or believe them if they do tell us.  because they're mortified.  they've been told if it happens to them its their fault.  disgusting.  if you're not pissed off at all this shit then you too are disgusting.  if you are discouraged by what's happening then lets start to change things.  create space where the women in your life feel safe to talk to you.  let them know you have their back and that you will always be there for them.  talk to your loved ones....we can change all this...vote these priveledge assholes out in your midterm elections,  the most important vote is happening november 6 2018 #midtermelections #metoo #womenshouldruntheworld

text:
i used to be scared to death to speak up because i couldn‚Äôt bear to ‚Äúhurt someone‚Äôs feelings.‚Äù i still hate when feelings get hurt. it‚Äôs fucking painful (usually for all involved, unless you‚Äôre a psychopath.) but bearing hurt feelings is part of life. as women, we truly are taught to people-please. i rarely meet a woman who has not struggled with the people-pleaser complex at some point in her life. at this point it‚Äôs so cliched to say that i wonder if people can actually take it in. but it‚Äôs true: when women speak up, we risk being ostracized, called bitches or worse, minimized or dismissed. it happens all the time. the #metoo movement created awareness about how many women are sexually assaulted. think about all that goes on that is not ok but is not sexual assault. there is a lot in that space leading up to assault that needs to change as well.i am not saying life is easy for men, but i am saying that this is not something most can understand in the core of their beings like women can.
i remember having a conversation with a gentleman about a job. i had previously held the job that he was currently going for. he was not as qualified now as i was then. he told me what they offered him, which was more than what they had offered me, and i said, ‚Äúdid you take it?‚Äù and he said, ‚Äúno i told them i would never work for so little.‚Äù so they offered him more. my jaw dropped. for many reasons. the main reason being that he said this with such matter-of-fact-ness. this was simply the world he lived in. i remember being in awe that he somehow innately knew (his description) to do this and that they listened. 
i am so impressed with all the beautiful women #speakingup today! and for the good men (there are so many!) showing up, speaking up, and choosing to evolve masculinity into its highest form ‚Äî where it honors the feminine. the old king must fall.

text:
thoughts on everything i‚Äôve seen posted with regards to the kavenaugh case... how do you prove a man grabbed your vagina while walking past you at a concert? how do you prove you got pinned in a staircase and groped faster than you could even scream for help? how do you prove that you were raped in the back of his car if he was kind enough to use protection? how do you prove that he was the one who broke into your hotel room and cut the crotch out of a pair of your panties? how do you prove that a stranger reached his hand into the back of your pants and tried to put his fingers into your body while walking in a huge crowd of revelers? how do you prove that a 27 year old raped you when you were 15 by convincing you that you were in some sort of relationship? how do you prove that the police officer that responded to the sexual assault of you and 3 of your friends was asking you to come home with him and licking his lips at you as your signed your statement? how do you prove that a security guard tried to stop the elevator so you‚Äôd be stuck with him after you rejected his advances? how do you prove a border officer telling you what he wants to do to you in broken english every time you crossed the border for almost 3 years? how do you prove that your boss put pressure on you to have sex with him because he‚Äôs ‚Äúyour boss and my wife doesn‚Äôt even care‚Äù. how do you prove that none of it happened at all? 
how do you know he‚Äôs not a loving father/husband/son/uncle? 
does his violation of you change how his loved ones perceive him? does his love for his family negate his violation of you? does violation of one woman mean a disrespect for all women? do we want to know all of the secrets of all of our men? do we want them to know all of ours? do any of these questions even matter at all?

if a tree falls in the forest and no one is around to hear it... you‚Äôll need 5 male witnesses to confirm it happened. or one woman to burn the whole thing down. 
#thinkbeforeyoupost #metoo

text:
#wakeupearly and #getafterit thursday!!!! #backday #deadlifts and also the day each week that i catch up on @theporch from @watermarkchurch . this has been a great series dealing with the lies told to us by what we watch and listen to. love the biblical litmus test for ‚Äúshould we do this?‚Äù (drinking, the way speak, the way we act, etc.). will it offend? will it cause someone else to fall? does it call your values into question? does it glorify god?
__________

using lots of points from this week‚Äôs message for my daughters. also pretty relevant in what created men‚Äôs mentalities that led to the #metoo movement. bottom line: your value has been given by god. you can‚Äôt lose it. your value is not how you look, how good in bed you are. it is not your past. your value is given by god. ‚Äúyou have been made in my image.‚Äù ~ genesis 1:27. women are told ‚Äúuse your body to get what you want‚Äù and men are told ‚Äúuse women to get what you want.‚Äù both are lies from the enemy. men, treat women as you would your mother or sister (1 timothy 5:2). women: the bait you use will determine the fish you catch
________

maybe your week has been #strong ? good! one more day! push hard on friday. everyone else is coasting through. disciplined people push through, friday is the day #excellence is shown. let everyone else be lazy. do today what they won‚Äôt so that tomorrow you will do what they can‚Äôt. #betterthanyesterday

#speakup !

i can't hear you! 
your voice. it's behind your hand. 
muffled with the sweet taste of truth
but your brain. stopping you from taking a stand. 
i know you're there!
you're fighting. wondering if you can withstand.
the people not believing, your reputation questioned.
it may not be ideal, but things rarely go as planned. 
don't be afraid.
courage. this is the time to band.
there are many of us. united, we will win. 
your voice. deserves to be in front of your hand. ¬©natasha wiebe

text:
attending:

keeping black girls at the center of #metoo.  this event is sponsored by: a long walk home.

many testimonials, spoken word, video presentations and reflections.  our girls haven‚Äôt been protected!  our innocent babies are left to be ravaged by this salacious society that sees black women and girls as sexual deviants.

when they go missing, there is rarely a real search for them or a real sense of urgency.

who will protect our girls?  will it be our men?  i guess they will have to stop raping, molesting, harassing and assaulting them, objectifying them.  disrespecting them.  beating them.  cursing them.  hurting them... destroying them. making it rain on them.

perhaps then!  we can protect our girls.  girls become women.  who values black girls?

our girls, our women deserve protection.  they deserve to be able to play... to walk out side and smile without feeling afraid.... they deserve to be free from fear.

you can‚Äôt protect what you prey upon.  we need warriors in our community.  warriors who will love and protect our women.  where are: our warriors? 
check out tarana burke‚Äôs page.

text:
üîä #exactly #payattention #empowerment ‚Äî the #metoo movement, in addition to raising awareness, has given people the courage to speak up about the times they've been wronged, harassed, or assaulted. women around the world have spoken out and there are horror stories from everywhere.
-
with the cases of sexual assault on the rise, there seems to be no escaping the predators. so, jackson katz, a social researcher, asked men and women what they did on a daily basis to avoid being ‚Äòsexually assaulted‚Äô.
-
the results are jaw-dropping.
-
author jennifer wright shared the result of the research. ‚Äújackson katz, a social researcher, asked men what they do on a daily basis to avoid being sexually assaulted. then he asked women, ‚Äù she tweeted along with a picture of the answers given.
-
the replies, arranged in a chart, is long and shows the stark contrast between the men, who had nothing to bother about, and the women, whose list could go forever.
-
drew mckenna shared a passage from a book by author jackson katz called the macho paradox: why some men hurt women and how all men can help.
-
in his book, jackson katz wrote "at first there is a kind of awkward silence as the men try to figure out if they've been asked a trick question. the silence gives way to a smattering of nervous laughter. occasionally, a young a guy will raise his hand and say, 'i stay out of prison.'"
-
"this is typically followed by another moment of laughter, before someone finally raises his hand and soberly states, 'nothing. i don't think about it.'"
-
this is not a meme - it's a result of someone's research. that, in our opinion, is the scariest part. it's not that men do not get assaulted, but the fact that crime against women is growing so rapidly is alarming.

„Éª„Éª„Éª
üîä #exactly #payattention ‚Äî the #metoo movement, in addition to raising awareness, has given people the courage to speak up about the times they've been wronged, harassed, or assaulted. women around the world have spoken out and there are horror stories from everywhere.
-
with the cases of sexual assault on the rise, there seems to be no escaping the predators. so, jackson katz, a social researcher, asked men and women what they did on a daily basis to avoid being ‚Äòsexually assaulted‚Äô.
-
the results are jaw-dropping.
-
author jennifer wright shared the result of the research. ‚Äújackson katz, a social researcher, asked men what they do on a daily basis to avoid being sexually assaulted. then he asked women, ‚Äù she tweeted along with a picture of the answers given.
-
the replies, arranged in a chart, is long and shows the stark contrast between the men, who had nothing to bother about, and the women, whose list could go forever.
-
drew mckenna shared a passage from a book by author jackson katz called the macho paradox: why some men hurt women and how all men can help.
-
in his book, jackson katz wrote "at first there is a kind of awkward silence as the men try to figure out if they've been asked a trick question. the silence gives way to a smattering of nervous laughter. occasionally, a young a guy will raise his hand and say, 'i stay out of prison.'"
-
"this is typically followed by another moment of laughter, before someone finally raises his hand and soberly states, 'nothing. i don't think about it.'"
-
this is not a meme - it's a result of someone's research. that, in our opinion, is the scariest part. it's not that men do not get assaulted, but the fact that crime against women is growing so rapidly is alarming.
‚Äî

text:
i‚Äôm not on any political sides, i‚Äôm actually not a registered democrat or republican. i don‚Äôt know much politically, but some spiritually & i know about humans to the core & care radically. i‚Äôll make conversation with anyone, anywhere so i can have human connection because i think it‚Äôs life giving and part of how god wanted all of us to be. not strangers. so when the kavanaugh thing happened when i was on vacation, i instantly gravitated to the woman, but felt compassion for both. i‚Äôm a survivor through and through when it comes to sexual assault. the number one thing i needed and wanted in my soul was to be believed. this isn‚Äôt a political post but i‚Äôll share this:  our natural state at our core is subtle, receptive and open. it's our ego, (false self), that wants to defend, kick & close up.
it feels more natural to live in the ego because we have all been hurt, & we are hurting still. we become threatened, which is exactly what has happened with the media this past week. on both sides. male, female, dem, rep etc
but we desperately need that natural state that doesn't come easy for us to come out. others need that from us. we need it to breathe easier. it's ok to be scared, but human connection & seeing people is more important than any opinion or agenda, & experience always trumps both. so i have to ask myself, what am i threatened by when my ego takes over?
-i'm afraid that my stories of assault aren't valid
-i'm afraid of not being believed
-i'm afraid i'll get blamed for being assaulted, that it's my fault.
-i'm afraid no one will affirm, listen or hug me.
-i'm afraid someone will think i'm a slut.
-i'm afraid to speak up because there really is no "evidence", this isn't a murder case after all.
-i'm afraid i'll be judged and i'll go even deeper into my shame i've carried for years.
-i'm afraid he'll get off without punishment
-i'm afraid he won't have to be accountable.
-i'm afraid my voice of innocence won't be heard, or taken seriously. -i'm afraid assault will become acceptable behavior, -i'm afraid matters of assault will get "swept under the rug".
-i'm afraid he'll do it again and again
women are afraid. #believewomen #metoo #abusesurvivor

üö®must readüö®
.
i was walking my dog before i was about to leave for the store when i was cat-called not once, not twice, but three times just walking down the street of my own neighborhood wearing (not that this is any factor in what happened) dirty gym clothes. as a woman, i feel the need to speak on this disgusting matter that we‚Äôve let slide for so many years, but is finally getting some attention.
.
i want to talk about cat-calling. this issue has gone on long enough. i‚Äôm fucking tired of the blatant disrespect for basic human decency. women get treated like dogs. some males (not all) think it‚Äôs ok to whistle, say ‚Äúhey girl‚Äù, howl, clap, or my favorite: have the balls to get angry at me when i don‚Äôt respond to said gestures. does this sound like the way you talk to a woman or a dog?!
.
this is not ok. i repeat this behavior is not ok.
.
you might think a quick whistle here or comment there is no big deal, but y‚Äôall don‚Äôt know the reality. the one comment adds up. you are one of many males who think it‚Äôs ok to do this shit and it gets to the point where women can‚Äôt do normal day to day activities without being harassed! .
don‚Äôt get me started on the ‚Äúshe shouldn‚Äôt be wearing that‚Äù bullshit. first of all, cat-calling happens no matter what we wear. i just proved that argument wrong by wearing completely covered stank ass gym clothes. and even if i was wearing a ‚Äúshort‚Äù dress or ‚Äúlow‚Äù top, it doesnt give you the right to treat me like a dog.
.
we are better than this. i know there are women in your life that if they came home and told y‚Äôall this story, you‚Äôd want to beat that guy‚Äôs ass. how about your mother? your grandmother, daughter, sister, cousin, niece? they most likely all have or will be cat-called too! are you proud of that probability? do you want your daughter to fear her daily activities? do you want your mom to be pulled up on and talked to in a vulgar manner? how about your niece who‚Äôs only 12? yup, it‚Äôs happening to her too.
.
we need to be better than this. no female should have to go through this their entire lives. it‚Äôs degrading, it‚Äôs paralyzing, it‚Äôs dehumanizing, and it is sick. .

text:
part 2: tw
.
when my civpro professor, who was also a former attorney with the aclu, told me i needed to talk to a lawyer i knew the trauma i had just spent the entire summer trying to get under control was only going to get worse.
.
after speaking to the dean of students about what happened, i met with the university‚Äôs attorney who admitted that there were major procedural errors which violated my civil rights, but there was nothing they could do without also harming his civil rights, so the committee was left to deliberate the information they had.
.
a few weeks later, right before halloween, the dean of the law school met with me to discuss the disposition.
.
now, i don‚Äôt have any memory of what happened the night i was assaulted. i made the irresponsible decision to drink way too much, way too fast before a school dance, and woke up in the hospital.
.
i take full responsibility for my individual recklessness that night. i completely deserved a nice hospital bill. i did not deserve, however, to have my bodily autonomy violated by someone i barely knew.
.
i was already totally humiliated about having to go to the hospital that night and i sensed something happened i didn‚Äôt know about, but when i later learned more details about what had transpired, first from one of my friends who came to the hospital with me & then straight from him, my embarrassment turned to abject horror.
.
the months that followed were filled with denial, confusion, shame, & guilt. i was working out excessively to try to burn off some of the adrenaline constantly flooding my body, but nothing helped quiet my mind from the anxiety i was feeling, especially after i decided to formally report what happened to my law school (they were aware of what happened before i even knew, but couldn‚Äôt move forward with investigating it without me).
.
anyway, because my testimony as it pertained to the incident was primarily hearsay and he chose not to testify at the hearing, the committee had to rely on his prior written testimony in which he admitted to fingering me, but denied actually having sex with me, despite bragging to his friends that we did the same night & telling me that we did a week later.

text:
who owns your womb?
.
despite all the evidence against him, it looks like the kavanaugh confirmation is a done deal. the investigation was a sham, completely controlled and limited to testimony orchestrated to exonerate him and give cover to those senators appearing to be on the fence. judge kavanaugh lied repeatedly under oath in the hearing as he did in previous hearings, but that doesn‚Äôt matter to the gop or to their base. our president lies daily, if not hourly. lying is allowed now, as is apparently, sanctioned sexual assault and harassment. what scares me most about this man is not his rigid belief system or that fact that he‚Äôs obviously unable to be impartial. what really freaks me out is that the man is an angry, revengeful bully.
.
while spouting conspiracy theories and going off on democrats, kavanaugh snarled, ‚Äúwhat goes around comes around.‚Äù two commentators on msnbc were discussing what that might have meant.  of course, i can‚Äôt read minds, but i‚Äôm almost certain kavanaugh was showing his internal thought process which was more than just wanting to get back at democrats. he was leaking his utter disdain and disrespect for women, thinking something like this: ‚Äúi‚Äôm going to get women back. they‚Äôre going to f%&*ing pay for what they‚Äôve done to me.‚Äù
.
the man is a bully, through and through; that was readily apparent at the hearing. he will seek revenge against those who have had the audacity to question his supreme right to be on the highest court in the land. he‚Äôll do any damage he can to the rights and freedoms of women.  i‚Äôm not sure what we can do at this point. at the very least, we need to show up big in november, but even that is looking less likely. it seems that the white male rage that trump continues to stoke at his rallies is riling up his base and now the blue wave we‚Äôve been hoping for is almost matched by a red one. .
who owns your womb? right now, you do. but it might not be for long. there has never been a more important time for women to get involved. we can't stop things, but we might be able to slow them down. @blueravenartist

text:
lets start with something current, the dr. christine ford story. october 27th, christine ford testified in front of the supreme court, accusing brett kavanaugh of attempting to rape her in 1982, when she was only fifteen years old. brett kavanaugh is trying to become of of the 9 justices of the supreme court, he worked on impeaching bill clinton and has had a life of privilege. in a weak and shakey voice told the story of how brett and his friend forced her into a room at a party, brett crawled on top of her, covering her mouth so she couldn't scream, and began to take off her clothes. "i believe he had the intent to rape me" ford said, the most disturbing part being her words "i'll never forget the laugh, one was ontop of me, both were laughing, like two buddies having a good time" these words shake me to the very core. kavanaugh's laywer questioned ford's credibility, saying though she claimed she had had one beer that night, she seemed to have remebered very little about the incident, she (instead of addressing the laywer directly, she directed her comment towards the jury) said "i'm sorry i can't remember more, i want to but i can't. her story is inspiring the nation and causing sparks of hope. there is however an uproar of negativity, several people claim she is lying, while donald trump even cared to comment. trump claimed that "it is not acceptable to lie in front of congress, and mocks her about how little she recalls. most disturbing, the supporters in the audience laugh wildy at his remarks. america calls her brave for sharing her story, i personally hope more women come out about sensitive issues like this one. here's hopings that america can change, and strive for retribution and justice for women like christine ford.
#justice #christineford #stopkavanaugh #metoo #timesup

text:
this month i‚Äôm reading #circe by @madeline.e.miller üìö

first off, the book is an enchanted page-turner. if you enjoy greek mythology - this is certainly your read! following the nymph as she lives her immortal life while meeting all the other characters, gods, monsters and humans, stories of which most of us read in school. she starts off as an innocent child who gets bullied, survives #metoo moment and becomes an amazing strong woman. üî∏
another day i tired on a pair of glasses with yellow lenses and the whole room just got bright as if the sun made its appearance. now, i wonder if i saw hermes delivering a message that i should go back and get them. gloomy weather, great sky, rain and winter are the opposite of what i love. in heart i‚Äôm a daughter of helios, god of the sun, there is no doubt about that. üî∏
so far i‚Äôm enjoying this book and i realize that i probably wouldn‚Äôt have stumbled upon it if it wasn‚Äôt for a book club. i joined it right away on my third day in japan. as a wife who has to move every couple of years, finding and reaching out to groups was and is one of my grounding tools. #gratitudeoftheday

text:
i keep seeing comments from people who don't understand why dr. ford's testimony was so convincing so i wanted to share some excerpts from the article written by a psychologist: "one of the few kinds of memory that gets instantly preserved ‚Äî sometimes forever ‚Äî is that caused by trauma ... that‚Äôs why victims tend, on average, to be more reliable reporters than perpetrators ... by speaking out and then testifying before congress, ford has put both herself and her family at great risk ... the consequences for kavanaugh are exactly the opposite. the payoff for denying that the incident occurred, or for denying that he was a heavy drinker in high school and college, are almost obscenely positive ... generally speaking, when someone is evasive under questioning, as kavanaugh was throughout his testimony, that‚Äôs a strong indication that he or she is hiding things. anger and indignation can also be tell-tale signs." #trumpchicken üê•

text:
attention women + families electing to birth in hospitals. stop scrolling and take a few minutes to read ü§∞üèºü§±üèºyesterday a discussion ensued at @freebirthsociety about needing a strong #metoo movement in the birthing community focusing on how a lack of specific consent for physical contact primarily in hospitals during birth is interpreted by many as a form of rape-entering a woman‚Äôs vagina without asking her to be more precise.
ü§±üèºü§∞üèºi entered the discussion by agreeing with @freebirthsociety that pregnancy and birthing is not a medical condition, yet a natural life experience that our society has allowed to become categorized as medical. personally and professionally i view hospitals as a place one goes in only emergent situations, not to birth babies. if you choose to birth in a hospital, the moment you enter, you and your baby are considered a liability to their business. because this is the case, the paperwork you sign‚Äîyou know when your contractions are insane and you‚Äôre dilated over 3 cm‚Äî states in the fine print what you give the hospital permission to do. essentially you consent to the hospital doing what they deem necessary to deliver your child ‚Äúsafely.‚Äù this may be pressure to proceed with procedures you may not have had time to research such as use of forceps or pitocin or injection of hep b vaccination and vitamin k. ü§±üèºü§∞üèºif you‚Äôre reading this and this is all new to you, you‚Äôre not alone. i work with my pregnant patients to help develop birth plans to ensure chain of command is pre-agreed upon and respected during your birth. it‚Äôs imperative to spell out  exactly what you want and what you don‚Äôt and it should be submitted and signed by all staff. you can even schedule meetings with obstetrics and nursing staff if you‚Äôre in a practice where you don‚Äôt know which provider will be at your delivery. the bottom line is if you decide to birth in the hospital, protect yourself. ü§±üèºü§∞üèºmore in the comments...

text: i shared this to my facebook page yesterday, so i apologize if you‚Äôve seen it already. if you have not, here‚Äôs some context: there is currently a meme being circulated that shows images of a teenage dr. christine blasey ford and a teenage judge brett kavanaugh. the meme implies that because dr. ford had braces, glasses, and didn‚Äôt look like she was the popular girl straight out of a 1980s molly ringwald movie, she couldn‚Äôt have been the target of an attempted sexual assault. truly heinous. this particular meme was shared by someone who sits on the rutherford county board of education. disturbing, right? my sister, being as vocal as me, pointed out how troublesome it was for an elected official to share such a despicable meme, and made clear the type of message he was sending to victims of sexual assault here in our school system. she received a lot of feedback from those who agreed with her, but also a lot of feedback from people defending this man‚Äôs decision to share the meme in the first place | in slide 1 above, you‚Äôll see my sister‚Äôs statement after voicing her concerns and then being verbally attacked, slides 2-5 are thoughts i shared in response to ashley‚Äôs post, and slide 6 is a photo of me at age 11, just for reference. | i don‚Äôt expect this post to generate a bunch of ‚Äúlikes‚Äù; it‚Äôs not pretty, it‚Äôs not fun, it‚Äôs not enjoyable. but, with kavanaugh‚Äôs confirmation seeming more and more inevitable, i feel it is my duty to share my truth, my own experiences, right now, more than ever before, and that is what i am doing. #believesurvivors #stopkavanaugh #believewomen #metoo #metoomovement #supportsurvivors #ibelieveher #ibelievechristineblaseyford #cancelkavanaugh #whyididntreport

text:
one droplet of hope is all it takes and some days it may seem impossible. .
to all of my survivors out there (of every gender), i hear you. i see you. i believe you. i stand by you.
.
.
i was at a trauma training this past weekend and was struck by the concept of ‚Äúintent versus impact.‚Äù .
.
there are well intentioned people out there who are causing harm and retraumatizating others through their words. others are doing it with intent to harm. regardless of who is speaking, the impact is the same, harm and trauma. .
you are strong. you are resilient. you are powerful.
.
.
#survivor #metoo #truthspeaking #empowered #healing #unitedconsciousness #thetimeisnow #standup #iwontbesilenced #ipreview

text_retweet:
the power of dancing with the dark feminine üëèüèº‚ú®‚ú®‚ú® #repost @laurahesp „Éª„Éª„Éª
i get a lot of flack for being so open, for being unapologetic about things other people are ashamed to share, for being too big and too loud and too opinionated.
.
i get flack for sharing my struggles, being fluid, being consistently inconsistent, and for having real, human emotions and mental struggles. for wearing my heart on my sleeve, my pants, my hat, my shoes, my face, everywhere. i am my heart.
.

but everything i am told to lessen, to hush, to keep a secret and to bury, has unlocked something in thousands of people. that is a gift, that is empowerment, that is solidarity.
.
and that is something i will never give up. ‚ú®‚ú®‚ú® #darkfeminine #womensangerrelease

text:
we showed up our numbers with ydsa (cu and auraria), umas y mexa, the collective, denver iso, and folks from a number of student organizations for a couple reasons. .
.
(i)to show that tpusa is the minority here in believing that rape culture is a myth. (ii) to show our solidarity with survivors, on a campus where rape culture has been a big problem. this had been a problem even before survivors bravely spoke out against kavanaugh -- a person who could possibly overturn roe v wade if confirmed to a position in scotus. .
.
we will continue to confront groups who treat rape culture as a thing to be "debated". the existence of rape culture is no debate. it is a continuation of an attack on all non-male bodies in a sexist society. .
.
we stand with survivors, plain and simple. .
.
join us in future meetings/protests in organizing to fight for a world without sexism.
.
.

text:
the collective energy right now is shifting. it feels like there's so much purging, reliving traumas, and trying to heal that there's just so much to feel all at once. i know i'm feeling the collective of those whose voices have not been heard or who have been heard and no justice taken, in addition to my own #metoo stories. it's a solemn time for the planet. but i've found some peace and raising my vibration through reiki, binaural beats, music with certain healing frequencies and nourishing myself with healthy foods and beverages. .
.
let yourself fully grieve so that you can heal and let go...because once you let go fully, then you are intentionally choosing to vacate the space your pain left. that then allows you to leave the space empty or to fill it with something lighter and brighter that serves your higher self.
.
.

text:
james fortune is a grammy award winning gospel singer who in 2015 committed domestic abuse against his wife and son. he gave an interview about what an abuser was and how it affected him. this portion of the interview intrigued me for one, i never heard an abuser speak out and two, he said it wasn't what she did but power and control he was missing in his life. abuse is never about you, but what the abuser is lacking in their life. stop taking on the abuse for something you caused. you didn't. they have demons they can't release and are projecting on you. be free from their problem

text:
i don‚Äôt often post back to back. and i‚Äôm aware that bringing up politics on a page that promotes inclusiveness and love can be tricky. but my intention isn‚Äôt divisive. much the opposite.  making these phone calls to senators today regarding the supreme court justice nomination makes me feel called to speak up. 
like many women globally, hearing dr. ford speak and seeing the subsequent reaction, including the president of the united states mocking her, a survivor of sexual abuse, triggered me. deeply. things i had buried to deal with another day/month/year/decade have launched themselves to the surface. 
sometimes we think we‚Äôre all healed. or at least that we‚Äôve let go of any pain, we‚Äôve moved on, we‚Äôre survivors. even when you reflect back, that strength remains. either that or you shove it so far into the back of your mental closet that it will never see the light of day. or so you think...
sometimes it takes something else. sometimes it takes the small niggling knowledge that you never ‚Äúdealt with‚Äù things. 
and sometimes it takes seeing a woman stand up before the entire world and speak up. because she had to. because she knew it was the right thing to do. all the while knowing that her life would never be the same. that it may be in danger. as may the lives of her loved ones. knowing that she could be ridiculed. or shamed. made to feel like a liar. or worst of all, believed and ignored. that she, and all other women on this planet don‚Äôt matter. not above the agenda of a man. 
sometimes, it takes seeing that woman, and the way she was treated, to bring out a tidal wave of collective hurt, rage, sadness and shame that women worldwide have experienced. over and over again. 
i spoke up back then. almost 10 years ago. terrified of the consequences of the threats placed against me. for my safety. for my family. for the outcome. but only because i had a fortress of women, and men, surrounding me and supporting me. but even then it was terrifying. even then it was the most difficult, painful experience of my life. and the worst part? text:
20 years ago, this show started. it inspired a whole generation of women to become more open with discussing themselves and their sexuality.
the show definitely fueled my fashion explorations and heavily guided i was, by the genius of patricia field. .
i recently read an interview with her on her time styling these iconoclastic 4 ladies. she had so much influence on an era of fashion and lent such an attitude of fun and whimsy into the world, teaming couture gowns with dollar store accessories. years later i was in nyc around my birthday and i stumbled across the @patriciafield shop. my joy was palpable. my eyes landed on these ridiculous sunnies. i somehow convinced my broke self that i absolutely needed these @itsjeremyscott x @lindafarrow sunglasses as a birthday present to myself and also as a homage to the creative juiciness that patricia had shared through the show for so many years. .
i have them somewhere, so i hope i get to wear them one day to a greek god‚Äôs themed day rave party... whenever that manifests. ü§î
.
who else adored sex and the city? i feel like many themes we currently discuss about #womensrights #metoo and #lgbt and the many other ways we campaign for equality were helped along by the open and often abrasive themes that were discussed in this show. so thanks in many ways to all the #sexandthecity staff... you opened up a world for many young women to be bold, make mistakes and keep fresh and challenging dialogue on the tip of our tongues.
.
#inspo #fashioninspo #satc #patriciafield #jeremyscott #lindafarrow #fashion #stylist #fashionblogger #missoni #rainbow #gayrights

text:
üó£ take a moment today to think about voices. everyone has a voice.
so why is it that our voices aren‚Äôt always listened to?and why is it that we don't always listen?
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
growing up girl in the evangelical world, i was taught to see my body as a liability, and men‚Äôs bodies as my responsibility.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
bc if i wasn‚Äôt careful, i might cause a man to lust‚Ä¶ or worse, to act on it. countless times, purity speakers and workbooks compared the purity of our bodies to crumpled toothpaste tubes, unwrapped lollipops, used pieces of gum, etc. üç≠üç´üç¨
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
a family member told me to stop wearing tank tops around other family members because i could cause them to think sexual thoughts, and that would be a sin. they wanted to protect me, but they were only teaching me that i was responsible even for family.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
üåë when i hear women raised in #purityculture say that assault is a woman‚Äôs fault, i get why. years of training teach us to listen only to one kind of voice.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
these are the lies: it didn‚Äôt happen, you just want attention.
and even if it did happen, it was because you wanted attention too.
notice a pattern here? ü§î
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
so many survivors say nothing because they fear they won‚Äôt be heard.
and so many survivors have been speaking anyway.
are you hearing us?
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i want to hear you. i want you to be heard. and i believe you. i believe you. i believe you.

text:
so my ass made it out of bed after a little over a week  yesterday and that put me back in it today.
been a real struggle since the hurricane. job prospect lost. artist block so i haven't been taking commissions. got a black eye and my finger nail ripped off. fist bumped by a lady cop in maryland. thrown out of a winning game for my team. sick af and i can't do anything about it. restarted keto 3 days ago and i want pears. so yeah, i'mma complain some.
that said. i do have some things still in the works. finding decent printers. learning how online trade works. finding a website builder. business loan. lighting. camera. etcetera.
i'm ready to get well and get started moving on to bigger and better things. making small goals and accomplishing them to reach bigger goals.

text: testimonial: ‚Äúmy whole life is a testament - sexually abused for years...sexually promiscuous from an early age. since i was in elementary school i knew two things: how to have sex and that something was watching me. i always talked to god. i didnt talk to anyone else about what was going on. besides having sex so often with different people i was so concerned with trying to do what i thought made me a good person. it made me become way too accomodating. the mix of it all made me way too submissive. i didnt speak up for myself a lot of times. i accepted anything. i continued to be verbally and physically abused by my lifelong abuser and other guys i got involved with. i was so messed up mentally that i had a break down in college and finally went to see a counselor. and i was introduced to islam. in the meantime though i did so many reckless and dangerous, really dangerous, and self loathing things. all with the guise of being a happy, strong, easy going, party girl - and god still favored me and brought me to islam. to know true peace and happiness is truly a result of studying and practicing islam and seeking god's grace. i think it‚Äôs because of prayer and talking to god.  when i say i really could not be here right now, not alive right now, i think of some of the places i‚Äôve been mentally and literally. god is so good. islam is true peace. allahu akbar‚Äù #canigetanameen

text:
profiles in courage: dianne darr couts
_____________
dianne grew up with her brothers at a missionary kid (mk) boarding school in guinea, west africa where they and their classmates were abused. after confronting the mission agency that ran the school and urging action for many years, eventually an independent commission of inquiry verified that spiritual, mental, physical, and sexual abuse had occurred at mamou alliance academy. dianne and her group of advocates continue to be contacted by adult mks needing help and support on their journeys to justice and healing. mk safety net was formed for that purpose in 2003. 
their ministry does not serve only children who are mks, but many adult survivors of abuse, a sad legacy of many church organizations that lack oversight and accountability. it was rare to come forward with abuse stories in the mid-1990s, and dianne and her group were accused of "trying to tear down missions" when our goal was to effect change in how missions cared for their mks and, most importantly, how reports of child abuse in mission settings were handled. 
dianne enjoys encouraging others and cheering people on, spending time with her grandchildren, traveling, writing, and gardening. she is currently reading karr‚Äôs ‚Äúthe art of memoir‚Äù and hagerdorn‚Äôs ‚Äúbeyond the river,‚Äù a book about the underground railroad in ohio. 
more than anything, dianne enjoys laughing around a table with family and friends.
_____________

who says you can post a "tongue out tuesday" picture on a thursday?  i was one of the few white house staffers, allowed into the secure room with the senators today.  i read the entire fbi report.  their summary form 302, is very clear, there are some breeds of dogs that are only allowed to stick their tongues out on tuesday and golden doodles are not included in this specific day criteria.  therefore, on behalf of other doods who were unable to make it to washington today - it's ok to post with your tongue out on thursday as well as tuesday's.  if anyone hassles you or bullies you for your posting choice, i pray you will go see you senator today!!!! i heard daddy say they could literally vote on this as early as saturday.  it's all but confirmed, this is huge, doodles unite!  we can and will make a difference!  lol üêæjaxon

text: as open as i've been about my experience with violent relationships, i've told very few people about my experience with sexual assault. i was raped when i was 16, by someone i was dating. he was 19 and i heard later that he did the same thing to other girls. i also heard he was on steroids for sports, which, not to excuse him, can ramp up your aggressiveness and violent tendencies. the assault happened really fast, but it was the most excruciating physical pain i've ever experienced. i couldn't walk the next day. it took me a long time to admit to myself i had been raped. i'm sharing this because i think all too often people still believe violence against women isn't common. i know countless women and men who have been assaulted. #metoo #believesurvivors

text:
today is the day.
for over a two years now i believe that how women and minorities are being treated has to change. but i never felt that i could do something about it.
well my time of procrastinating on is over now. i will do something about it. i will act. i will contribute to the movement of gender equality and equality concerning every human being on earth. 
it's my duty as a privileged person to support those that don't have these privileges. it's my job to make this world a better place. and it should be yours too.

text:
fair warning: this is going to be a fairly long read, and some of you may want to grab a large glass of water, milk, dr pepper, jack daniels, or whatever it is that you like to take your pills with, because this pill is going to be rather hard to swallow.
a couple of weeks ago i made a post about feminism. how feminism isn't about being better than anyone, it's about being equal. somehow, somewhere, people got the wires crossed, and started thinking it meant women had to have more rights, or be better than their male counterparts. that is completely untrue. that is superiority, not feminism.
now if women truly want to be considered equals, men must also be treated as equals. that means all of the double standards must be annihilated. if you can dredge up something from 10, 20, 30+ years ago with no evidence, ruin someone's future, reputation, homelife, etc, then you better be ready for someone to do the same to you. 
but guess what, men can't do that. why? because of the double standard of "guys like it when you do that." guess what skanky sally, not every man likes that. even if a man does like it, you shouldn't be able to do anything unless he specifically gives you permission to do so. 
since that seems to be the phrase of choice, "i never gave him permission to touch me." no, but you did grind your pelvis against his for a good hour or more, and never once said, "no, or stop." what conclusion did you think he was going to arrive at after your lap dance session? unless you're a stripper, your argument is invalid, because that's what they get paid to do. even then, you must have their permission to touch.
furthermore, if you falsely accuse someone of sexual misconduct or sexual assault, and it is found to be false, you should have to serve the time that individual would've had to serve,  if they were found guilty. it's only fair, since "equality." before you get your feathers all ruffled, that's what women have wanted for years. equality.

for those of you that don't keep up with me (because frankly, who would want to?), i'm a feminist. i am part of the #metoo, and i also stand behind #himtoo.

republican sen. ben sasse drops a bombshell on the debate over brett kavanaugh's nomination to the supreme court

bryan logan 
oct 3, 2018, 10:17 pm et Ôøºjim bourg-pool/getty imagessen. ben sasse of nebraska.

republican sen. ben sasse of nebraska gave an impassioned speech on sexual assault and the #metoo movement on the senate floor wednesday night.

sasse also dropped a bombshell about where he stands on brett kavanaugh, president donald trump's second nominee to the supreme court. "i urged the president to nominate a different individual. i urged the president to nominate a woman," sasse said.

he recounted the experiences of two personal friends he said were raped, adding that the #metoo movement has been "complicated," but also a "very good thing." then sasse turned back to trump: "we all know that the president cannot lead us through this time."

text:
tomorrow morning, the senate votes on kavanaugh. keep fighting. #believesurvivors. be loud. melt the phone lines. show up. here‚Äôs what you can do via @jesslivmo and @sarahsophief call now:
‚†Ä
ak 
@lisamurkowski 202-224-6665
me
@senatorcollins 202-224-2523
nd
@senatorheitkamp 202 224-2043 (who just committed to voting no. call her & thank her).
wv 
@sen_joemanchin 202-224-3954 ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî if we don't believe we can win, we will not. when it feels dark is when we double down. worried we can't #stopkavanaugh? do something.
‚†Ä
call your senator.
go to a march.
message your friends and ask them to call. 
get to hart atrium if you are in dc. 
the *only* reason we are at the point we are now in this process is because of us. we built this moment and we must fight tooth and nail until it is over. and it ain't over yet.

if mitch mcconnell had the votes, you better believe this would be done. and we know that a well places message from a constituent (ahem, #elevatorwomen) can change the process. 
nothing is a done deal until the end. and we have at least 24 hours to influence votes. so hop to it and fight like hell. #stopkavanaugh #cancelkavanaugh #timesup #metoo #whatsatstake #keepshowingup #stayhuman

text:
new podcast @bryannasayingthings .
ep.27 family constellations, healing generational trauma, talking about sexual assault.
.
in this episode, we talk about: 
marine‚Äôs therapy modality ‚Äì family constellations ‚Äì what it is.
.
how it works marine‚Äôs background and what led her to her life‚Äôs work.
.
how we make healing more complicated than it needs to be.
.
what epigenetic is and how this science proves that trauma can be passed down through family generations.
.
how healing yourself really heals your whole family.
.
why growth is a mandatory part of every relationship marine and bryanna‚Äôs experiences with sexual assault, why it is important to talk about, and how the way we talk about it matters.
.
plus much more‚Ä¶ .
.
marine selenee‚Äôs words/quotes
.
healing is not complicated. we make it complicated.
.
your pain becomes your purpose. i was in pain with my father. i was in pain with my story because i was like, that was not fair. why me? but actually, why not me?
.
we will have ups and downs, we will have obstacles, we will lose people that we really, really love, but at the end it‚Äôs about having fun. enjoying the ride. making connection. helping others. loving and loving again. this is the miracle of life.
.
i think this is the only thing we want: just telling our story, our truth. we don‚Äôt want the victim status, we don‚Äôt want pity, we just want to be recognized.
.

text:
these past weeks warranted a brief blogging hiatus for me, a silence screaming righteous indignation. the words simply weren‚Äôt there. or they fell in a sodden torrent that left me feeling like i‚Äôd been drenched in denim, heavy and chafed.
and yet. i never thought i‚Äôd take such comfort at the sight of so many unwilling to remain hidden. i see a revolution, and i want it painted black.
and yet and yet. a grief wells up inside me to see the veracity of story and lived experience on trial. an indescribable pain as i witness what happens when inconvenient and pernicious truths refuse silence. a sick familiarity born of knowing what follows the moment when one of those truths sheds an unflattering light on someone in power, someone who feels entitled to that power and to the comfort of being considered, blindly and without question, ‚Äúright,‚Äù someone whom we‚Äôd rather think differently of, for whatever reason.
doubt, denial, excuses sink and swirl like some cloying, eclipsing smog. and we who bear witness to the story told, the unfolding, find ourselves in the squirm-invoking position of having to decide what responsibility we will take, what actions, whether we will turn our heads away from or towards those deceptions and misdeeds demanding we admit that some among us possess a capacity to do unspeakable harm.
and yet and yet and yet. we must be convinced to ‚Äúbelieve‚Äù certain stories, while others seem to go without saying, and i‚Äôm still sussing out what that says about us. i‚Äôm still sussing out the power i wield with my words and what that means for me, for the choices i make, for the stories i give voice to and tell. i‚Äôm still sussing out the enormous strength and tenacity and courage it takes to continue telling the stories that incite crises of integrity and self-preserving backlashes.
therein lies the power and struggle of telling true stories. that much, i know for damn sure, is true.

‚ò†Ô∏è #omg #wtf #nom #war ‚ò†Ô∏è if you know any bit of #history related to #internationaldevelopment and the #development of chemical fertilizers like #monsanto‚Äôs #roundup, this article will terrify you. #metoo. 
government-backed researchers in america are aiming to use virus-carrying #insects to genetically engineer crops ‚Äì raising fears the #technology could be used for biological #weapons.

a new article in the journal #science explores the shadowy program funded by the us defense advanced research projects agency (#darpa). the program aims to disperse infectious, genetically modified viruses that have been engineered to alter the chromosomes of crops ‚Äì using insects to spread the viruses to the #plants.

researchers have received more than $27m in contracts to pursue the genetic engineering scheme, in a program dubbed #insectallies.

the agency describes the research as a way to improve crop security: #bugs like aphids, leafhoppers and whiteflies will be used to spread a virus to plants including #corn and tomatoes, which will then impart beneficial genes making the plants resistant to #disease or drought.

but in the science article, an international team of scientists and lawyers warn that the technology could be put to more nefarious purposes, including military applications.

#whyididntreport exploded on social media, a rallying cry for those who had never gone public about their own sexual assault until then. ford‚Äôs testimony slowed the machinery of political power when it was fully in gear. an npr/pbs newshour/marist poll released oct. 3 found that 45% of respondents thought ford was telling the truth, compared to 33% who believed kavanaugh. that‚Äôs a marked shift from 1991, when americans sided with clarence thomas after anita hill accused him of sexual harassment. the facts remain unsettled, and ford‚Äôs testimony may not prevent kavanaugh‚Äôs confirmation. but it was a powerful warning that wealth, status and a record of professional accomplishments were no longer enough to override credible allegations of sexual assault, no matter when they occurred. text:
i‚Äôm working on this new painting for the @iadanonymous_artshow coming up at @100braidst while listening to @thatgirlbishop lay it down. and i‚Äôm thinking about the power of women, and how we continue forward in spite of every #metoo moment, big and small, that we have faced. .
i have to be honest, i‚Äôm struggling right now with all the media coveragep, as i know many survivors are. as @glennondoyle would say, it‚Äôs brutiful. our voices are being heard in a way that is unprecedented. the damage that has been done is starting to be recognized. that is both validating and excruciating. because we spend so much time telling ourselves that it wasn‚Äôt that bad, and now is the time of reckoning. now is the time that we say ‚Äúit really was that bad. and it still is.‚Äù
.
i am hopeful and devastated all at once.
.
the anonymous show gala opening night
100 braid st studios

text:
to help me escape from all the trauma i had experienced as a child, i developed in my mind an "escape personality" as i like to call it.

abdullah. that was my safe zone. this might sound crazy to some but 'abdullah' helped me so much. even all the way into adulthood. i think i only abandoned the idea a year ago, when i finally received the mental health support i needed.
i'm not ashamed to speak about this and in fact now see the humor in it, but one thing that breaks me is why a child ever needs to develop a fake friend to help them survive in the real world. why a child needs to become someone else in order to fight the demons. there were many days i became abdullah only to be able to see hope in another day. 
i posted this today because i was trying to make sense of it all. why i chose a male personality not a female one? why i chose that name? why i chose to free myself through something that did not exist?

i realised today that in my community, in my family, in my life in general, the male character played his role with my power than a female. i saw how many men escaped from being abusers and losers without even a slap on their wrist. i saw how a female was silenced. i saw the tears, the cheating, the money loving, the greed, the home wreck. i saw it all. i saw how fake they were and fake abdullah felt more real than they ever could be. i wanted to show them you can be a man but still love and be loved. abdullah was more of a man than they could ever be.
.
p.s. i do not re-read my posts. this is me raw and un-edited.
****************************************

text:
red lipstick has so many meanings to women. power. sexuality, boldness. glamour. confidence.

right now, red lipstick is being used as a show of solidarity with survivors of sexual trauma with some companies promoting the shade as a way of throwing 'shade' at what is happening culturally right now. 
part of healing as a survivor of any trauma is reclaiming your power and holding space for you. sometimes, a mantra or word of inspiration can be a reminder to reclaim your space! 
try it out- post a word where you can see it and look at it each day. notice what you feel like when you say it out loud or read it. simmer in it. let it flow. 
here are some ideas: 
#power #inspire #breathe #hope #bold #goddess #sexy #confidence #grace #peace #secure #love #magic #choice #happy #joy #mindful #freedom 
what is your word? 
#redlipstick #metoo #mentalhealth #survivor #medhat #ibelieveyou

text: missing this cabin and the shero cuddles it held. if you‚Äôre tired cause of the sexual assault conversations nationally right now, scroll right on by, my love. totally get where you are at. ‚ô•Ô∏è survivorship is a full-time gig right now, and that‚Äôs just a lot. i‚Äôm tired around the clock, and there‚Äôs so much in my routine that‚Äôs meant to be calming that just takes from me at the moment - tv, radio, facebook, instagram, magazines, normal chats with coworkers or cashiers or neighbors. it just pops up. the worst bit to me? i always feel a huge need to be real in love with me and real happy with who i became after my trauma when survivorship things are widespread and wow has that been too heavy to handle this month. i am super well versed in healing isn‚Äôt linear, but it‚Äôs harder realizing it also doesn‚Äôt end. you think it‚Äôs done and you did the love yourself thing. you fixed it. you loved you. no need to look back, wash those hands, step over the pieces, and be done with that tending yourself thing. and then it‚Äôs back. and sometimes it‚Äôs back when you aren‚Äôt wild about you, and you know it took so much love for you to get here and when it comes back at a slump in self-like, the less than liking you feels very... off kilter. like a bigger betrayal than you expected. you think you should just alternate to the deeply loving being you learned to be at one point to make it here... and that‚Äôs just not possible right now. you grew and changed and are healing differently now. and it feels like you have to still be that person that survived or at least show the love you showed and had. and it‚Äôs not always there. there‚Äôs no shiny ending to this post - it‚Äôs just a vibe. chances are given my follower-ship... it‚Äôs mutual with folks and if it‚Äôs not with you, it is with someone you love. throw them a love line, give them a break, offer some hugs. we are all figuring it out sloooooowly.

#repost from @womenforwomen ‚Äúthe past few weeks have brought up a lot of emotions in me, including anger. in my 20s i was raped. and since then i have been groped and aggressively sexually harassed multiple times. and yes i remember the minute details of how the attacks felt ‚Äì particularly the mocking refusal to stop. but i do not remember the name of the street, the exact date and time. there were no witnesses and i did not report. ‚Äúwhat would happen,‚Äù i asked myself then. no one would get caught, nothing would change, i would just sit and be scrutinized in a police station for hours, bare myself, feel mortified, and that would be that. so i didn‚Äôt report then. but the #metoo movement and talking to survivors of violence at women for women international compelled me to share my story last year and to continue to do so.‚Äù -laurie adams, women for women international ceo

read the rest of laurie‚Äôs blog on our website. link in bio.

text:
13 years old vs 25 years old‚è≥‚åõ
.
#tbt #throwbackthursday .
i still remember the day my cousin @justa_daydream took that photo on the left; it was for my very first default on myspace #ifeelold
.
within one day of posting that picture, i receiced dozens of messages, all from older men, telling me how hot i was and how sexy i was (which i hardly even knew what that meant), and i remember feeling so validated, like "oh, i'm so special; older men, mature men want me. they give me meaning." -- of course that's not exactly how my train of thought went, but if you're a woman reading this, you get what i mean.
.
now, at 25, i still receive messages from men who want to do things to me that make me drop my phone, gasp, and make my skin crawl for hours in response... however, i no longer let those comments slide. i either tell the man that i have been hurt and give him a chance to apologize, or i block him and refuse to hangout with him to avoid further toxicity.
.
i honestly can't wait to have a daughter because being a woman is a beautiful thing to be ‚ôÄÔ∏è however, i plan on teaching her so many things i wish i had known, such as, your self worth should never be in the hands of another; only you can decide your worth.
.
stay strong, and never give up, lovely ladies.

happening tonight! be there if you can! wear red and black. #wemarchtogether #insolidarity 
#repost @sacramentoactivism
„Éª„Éª„Éª
we invite you to join our solidarity vigil #cancelkavanaugh on thursday, october 4th! we will meet on the west steps of the capitol at 5:30 p.m.
.

5:30 p.m. - speaker line-up and survivor testimonies 
6:30 p.m. - candle light vigil honoring survivors 
wear red and black
.

tea lights and led lights are welcome during the vigil.
.

this event will have asl interpreters during the speaker portion of the gathering. 
kavanaugh has shown that he is hostile to women‚Äîfrom his record against women's health and autonomy to his record against workplace protections to the sexual assault allegations against him to the anger he displayed to female u.s. senators.
.
kavanaugh has shown that he has no credibility: he has lied repeatedly in confirmation hearings spanning two decades, and he lied again in his testimony regarding dr. christine blasey ford's credible allegation of sexual assault.
.
now is the time for all of us to come together and tell our senators to believe women and stop kavanaugh this week‚Äîand to show the country that women, and all of us, will hold republicans accountable on november 6.
.

kavanaugh would rule for a generation against reproductive freedom, health care, the environment, voting rights, workers‚Äô rights, lgbtq rights, and immigrant rights, while siding with big corporations, big money, and the trump agenda. and we can't let the white house rush and hamper an fbi investigation. the survivors who have stepped forward in recent weeks deserve better, as do we all.
.

senators in all fifty states must listen to their constituents, do their jobs to uphold the will of the people, protect the soul of our country and constitution, and block this nomination. together, we will fight to ensure brett kavanaugh never gets confirmed by the senate. we will #stopkavanaugh. join us.
.
